<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-24T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-24T19:00:00-05:00" n="1000" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1000">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/249d.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">American Consul at
                                    Chihuahua</gloss></hi>.<note n="2" xml:id="d1000fn2">Same to
                                consuls at Nogales, Ciudad Porfirio Diaz, Ciudad Juárez, Laredo, and
                                Ensenada.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-24T19:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 24, 1912—7 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The President’s proclamation of March 14 does not affect clothing, dry
                            goods, hardware, and foodstuffs, and Treasury Department has <pb facs="0874" n="758" xml:id="pg_758"/> issued orders to its officers
                            on the Mexican border to admit properly invoiced and manifested
                            shipments.</p>
                        <p>Exemption of dynamite for mines and other industrial purposes is still
                            under consideration by the Attorney General. Keep Department closely
                            informed about this.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>